00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.050
Probably the first
question for both of you

00:01:00.050 --> 00:01:01.740
is pretty simple,
which is, I mean,

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:04.300
you've both had
such amazing careers

00:01:04.300 --> 00:01:08.330
defining financial
expertise for the industry.

00:01:08.330 --> 00:01:09.790
Why the involvement
at Wealthfront

00:01:09.790 --> 00:01:12.540
at this point, maybe
just a retrospective?

00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:16.100
BURTON MALKIEL: Well,
from my standpoint,

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:19.100
it was largely because
I think most people get

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:25.400
just terrible financial
advice, and it's too expensive.

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:31.910
Most financial advisers charge
a very high fee themselves.

00:01:31.910 --> 00:01:35.850
And they are
conflicted in that when

00:01:35.850 --> 00:01:41.550
they suggest that you buy this
or that mutual fund, what's

00:01:41.550 --> 00:01:44.420
sort of little known
is that they usually

00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:47.570
get a payment from that
mutual fund company

00:01:47.570 --> 00:01:49.750
to put you in that mutual fund.

00:01:49.750 --> 00:01:52.260
They're high-cost funds.

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:54.920
And I've spent my life
studying the fact,

00:01:54.920 --> 00:02:01.620
as the introduction said,
that over time, very

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:06.460
high-cost mutual funds don't
beat the market-- rather,

00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:11.300
they underperform the market--
and that they underperform

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:17.240
the market by at least the
amount of their excess cost.

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:20.420
So you've got costs
of the adviser.

00:02:20.420 --> 00:02:24.980
You've got high-priced funds
and what the adviser recommends.

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:27.740
The advisor is
typically conflicted.

00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:30.480
And here, you have
something where,

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:34.630
with the advantage of
doing this with software

00:02:34.630 --> 00:02:37.850
and doing this
electronically, that you

00:02:37.850 --> 00:02:40.540
can give unconflicted advice.

00:02:40.540 --> 00:02:46.570
And we use the funds that I
have recommended all my life,

00:02:46.570 --> 00:02:51.630
low-cost index funds that
competition has now driven down

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:54.860
to have very close to zero fees.

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:57.750
So we can provide
this electronically.

00:02:57.750 --> 00:03:00.180
It's inexpensive.

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:04.810
I think it's as good advice
as any high-priced investment

00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:06.810
adviser will give you.

00:03:06.810 --> 00:03:09.980
And we can then,
particularly for funds

00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:16.930
that are over
$100,000, do things

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:20.270
like tax loss harvesting.

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:23.920
None of us can control what
the stock market's going to do,

00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:26.060
but the one thing
we can control is

00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:28.490
the things that
are controllable.

00:03:28.490 --> 00:03:32.030
And one of them is costs,
and one of them is taxes,

00:03:32.030 --> 00:03:35.800
and this we can do very
inexpensively electronically.

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:41.040
And I'm actually
very, very proud to be

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:44.090
a part of an
organization that I think

00:03:44.090 --> 00:03:47.119
is doing a great job for people.

00:03:47.119 --> 00:03:47.910
ADAM NASH: Charley?

00:03:47.910 --> 00:03:49.240
CHARLEY ELLIS: We differ.

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:53.290
Burt would say it's low cost
and a much better product,

00:03:53.290 --> 00:03:56.290
and I would say it's much
better product and low cost.

00:03:56.290 --> 00:03:59.260
ADAM NASH: [LAUGHS]

00:03:59.260 --> 00:04:01.830
CHARLEY ELLIS: Seriously, if
you look back over the last 50

00:04:01.830 --> 00:04:06.450
years, I think both of us
would be truly aggravated

00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:11.270
by the crowd we know best not
doing anything like a really

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:14.691
good job, and candidly,
charging quite large amounts.

00:04:14.691 --> 00:04:16.899
There are a lot of different
ways of looking at that,

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:18.649
and we can come back
to it if you want to.

00:04:18.649 --> 00:04:22.240
But it is very unsettling
to have the crowd

00:04:22.240 --> 00:04:26.610
that you're part charging a
lot and delivering a little.

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:28.070
So you're looking all the time.

00:04:28.070 --> 00:04:30.460
And when I heard
from Burt that he

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:32.260
was involved with
Wealthfront, seemed to me

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:34.170
like a great deal of sense.

00:04:34.170 --> 00:04:36.780
ADAM NASH: Well, I mean,
I'm glad you mentioned that.

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:39.220
You two have known each
other for a long time now.

00:04:39.220 --> 00:04:41.261
CHARLEY ELLIS: We were
born in the same hospital,

00:04:41.261 --> 00:04:43.234
so it goes back quite a ways.

00:04:43.234 --> 00:04:45.900
ADAM NASH: Do you want to tell a
bit about how you two first met

00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:47.110
and worked together?

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:48.750
I'm sure people would
love to hear it.

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:50.680
CHARLEY ELLIS: Do you remember?

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:54.590
BURTON MALKIEL: Well, I think
we have been-- of course,

00:04:54.590 --> 00:04:59.140
the first index fund was founded
by a company called Vanguard,

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:03.410
and Vanguard now is the
biggest index fund provider.

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:07.260
And they also provide
ETFs, which are basically

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:10.130
funds that trade as stocks.

00:05:10.130 --> 00:05:12.770
And they're basically--
the ones that Vanguard

00:05:12.770 --> 00:05:14.300
has are index funds.

00:05:14.300 --> 00:05:18.190
And Charley and I, for
a long period of time,

00:05:18.190 --> 00:05:22.250
sat next to each other
on the Vanguard board.

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:24.000
And I think one of
the reasons that we

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.789
got to really like
each other is that--

00:05:27.789 --> 00:05:29.080
CHARLEY ELLIS: Oh, it's agreed.

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:29.590
[LAUGHS]

00:05:29.590 --> 00:05:31.381
BURTON MALKIEL: Yeah,
that was the problem.

00:05:31.381 --> 00:05:34.130
We would all make a point,
and somehow or other,

00:05:34.130 --> 00:05:35.710
you and I always agreed.

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:38.890
And we sat next to each other.

00:05:38.890 --> 00:05:41.300
And if we didn't even talk,
we would just sort of nod.

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:44.290
So that was how it all started.

00:05:44.290 --> 00:05:48.520
And my god, I don't want to
count the number of years,

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:51.830
but it was long number of years.

00:05:51.830 --> 00:05:57.280
And we became friends
and became co-authors,

00:05:57.280 --> 00:06:02.310
because the little book
that's been featured

00:06:02.310 --> 00:06:07.040
is our attempt to
put down everything

00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:10.850
we know in a book that would
take an hour and a half

00:06:10.850 --> 00:06:11.930
to read.

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:13.984
And we had a lot of
fun doing it together.

00:06:13.984 --> 00:06:15.900
CHARLEY ELLIS: That's
if you're a slow reader.

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:18.740
BURTON MALKIEL: If you're
a slow reader, right.

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:20.630
ADAM NASH: [LAUGHS]
That's great.

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:24.090
I mean, Burt, this
isn't the first time

00:06:24.090 --> 00:06:26.780
I think you've been at Google.

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:30.436
In 2004, I remember
when Google went public.

00:06:30.436 --> 00:06:32.310
It was the big IPO at
the time, because there

00:06:32.310 --> 00:06:35.070
hadn't been a lot of
big IPOs in a few years.

00:06:35.070 --> 00:06:38.070
I thought Google did
something fairly unique

00:06:38.070 --> 00:06:40.130
given its dedication
to its employees

00:06:40.130 --> 00:06:43.830
and their financial health, is
that you were invited here--

00:06:43.830 --> 00:06:46.120
not here in the New York
office, but in Mountain View,

00:06:46.120 --> 00:06:48.990
in California-- to
talk to the employee

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:51.130
base about the markets,
and help prepare them

00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:55.030
for what it meant to have
wealth in the market.

00:06:55.030 --> 00:06:58.410
What was it like
speaking to Google 2004?

00:06:58.410 --> 00:07:02.180
BURTON MALKIEL: Actually, you
know, my first time at Google,

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:06.516
I had two main impressions.

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:15.110
First of all, I've been an
academic most of my life,

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:18.870
but started my investment
career as an investment

00:07:18.870 --> 00:07:20.560
banker in New York.

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:28.100
And as I got into
this business, we

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:31.640
had a training program of
about a half a dozen guys.

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:37.310
And we were going to be given
a lecture by the senior partner

00:07:37.310 --> 00:07:40.760
of the firm, and
the air conditioning

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:42.390
broke in the building.

00:07:42.390 --> 00:07:44.430
Actually, it was the
building 20 Broad Street,

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:48.290
right next to the New
York Stock Exchange.

00:07:48.290 --> 00:07:52.020
So we were all coat
and tie, obviously,

00:07:52.020 --> 00:07:57.090
and the other trainees
took their coats off.

00:07:57.090 --> 00:08:00.280
The senior partner then
started to address us,

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:07.620
and said, "it's OK when the air
conditioning breaks that you

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:10.850
can take your jackets
off," but then

00:08:10.850 --> 00:08:13.010
looked at one of
the trainees who

00:08:13.010 --> 00:08:16.740
had a short-sleeved shirt
on-- "but never, never,

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:19.080
never take your
coat off if you've

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:21.260
got a short-sleeved shirt on."

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:23.920
So this is how I came
into the business world.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:26.590
So you can imagine
my first impression

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:31.140
of going to Google of what
an informal place this was.

00:08:31.140 --> 00:08:35.230
People had t-shirts,
shorts, flip-flops.

00:08:35.230 --> 00:08:41.059
People were throwing
Frisbees inside the building.

00:08:41.059 --> 00:08:43.260
There were dogs running around.

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:45.510
And I couldn't
help but think back

00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:47.370
to the beginning of
my business career.

00:08:47.370 --> 00:08:48.810
And I say, oh my god.

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:51.670
I knew the West Coast was
always less formal than the East

00:08:51.670 --> 00:08:54.050
Coast, but what a
difference this is.

00:08:54.050 --> 00:08:57.340
And I also visited at the
time-- because I had known him,

00:08:57.340 --> 00:08:59.930
I'd been on a couple
of panels with him--

00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:04.220
Eric Schmidt, who was then the
CEO, was a Princeton trustee.

00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:08.720
And here was Eric Schmidt
in this little tiny office.

00:09:08.720 --> 00:09:10.880
And I was thinking of
the partners' offices

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:12.270
in the investment banks.

00:09:12.270 --> 00:09:15.470
And so the first
impression was, my god,

00:09:15.470 --> 00:09:17.940
what a different world
this was from the world

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:20.880
that I grew up in.

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:23.270
I think the second
impression that I had,

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:25.760
when you go into the
Google headquarters,

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:30.140
there's this huge map of
the world with lights.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:33.860
And every time
somebody does a search,

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:37.390
in whatever part of the world
it is, a light goes off.

00:09:37.390 --> 00:09:40.370
So you're looking at this
sort of map of the world,

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:44.580
and lights are blaring at you.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:47.579
It's like a Christmas tree.

00:09:47.579 --> 00:09:49.120
And everywhere-- I
mean, it must have

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:51.400
been three o'clock in
the morning in Tokyo,

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:55.110
but Japan was all lit up.

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:59.800
And you know, it occurred to
me, what a worldwide phenomenon,

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:02.820
and what an amazing
company this is,

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:05.690
and what a worldwide
company it is.

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:08.500
And also, as kind
of an economist who

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:10.970
is interested in
economic development,

00:10:10.970 --> 00:10:16.950
I thought, what a way of showing
the parts of the world that

00:10:16.950 --> 00:10:21.380
are undeveloped, because as
you looked at the map, the only

00:10:21.380 --> 00:10:27.900
dark part was between sub-Sahara
Africa and southern Africa.

00:10:27.900 --> 00:10:31.470
And there were no
lights going on there.

00:10:31.470 --> 00:10:36.860
And you realize, how could
you build a better show where

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:41.420
the world is the economically
developed and where it isn't?

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:45.852
So those were kind of my
first two impressions.

00:10:45.852 --> 00:10:48.875
It was an absolutely
wonderful experience.

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:57.550
We were giving out parts
of my "Random Walk" book.

00:10:57.550 --> 00:11:00.990
And at lunch, Mario
Batali was there,

00:11:00.990 --> 00:11:03.150
and he was cooking
for all the Googlers,

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:05.900
and I traded books with him.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:08.360
And it was one of
my-- you think of

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:10.720
the unforgettable
experiences in your life,

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:12.884
and that was one of them,
my first visit to Google.

00:11:12.884 --> 00:11:13.550
ADAM NASH: Yeah.

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:17.150
Well, it's fascinating,
because Google came public,

00:11:17.150 --> 00:11:21.010
like I said, a few years
after the first big market

00:11:21.010 --> 00:11:23.630
crash, the kind
of 2000 to 2001--

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:26.900
at least the big market
crash in recent memory.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:30.090
And then just a few years
later, of course, in 2008,

00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:34.320
we had the massive
financial dislocation.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:37.020
And this is a question
for both of you, but how

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:40.880
do you feel that affects the
advice that you give people

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:43.590
or how they receive it, now that
they've been through not one,

00:11:43.590 --> 00:11:46.089
but two of these big events?

00:11:46.089 --> 00:11:47.755
CHARLEY ELLIS: It
gathers the attention.

00:11:51.430 --> 00:11:54.780
It depends on your
own perspective.

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:57.180
We're both of us in
an age cohort where

00:11:57.180 --> 00:11:59.800
we've been around long enough
so you can't help but think

00:11:59.800 --> 00:12:02.890
about times way back
and stuff like that.

00:12:02.890 --> 00:12:06.190
Markets go up and down.

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:08.067
Mr. Morgan was one
asked, what do you

00:12:08.067 --> 00:12:09.150
think of the stock market?

00:12:09.150 --> 00:12:10.340
He said, it will fluctuate.

00:12:10.340 --> 00:12:13.550
And sure enough, still does.

00:12:13.550 --> 00:12:17.360
Sometimes it fluctuates
like a punch in the face,

00:12:17.360 --> 00:12:20.920
and sometimes it's like a
beautiful woman's soft touch,

00:12:20.920 --> 00:12:23.349
just everything is
working out perfectly.

00:12:23.349 --> 00:12:25.890
But most the time, it's to sort
of wobbling around out there.

00:12:25.890 --> 00:12:29.300
And I think it's
dreadfully dangerous,

00:12:29.300 --> 00:12:31.690
because it attracts
your attention.

00:12:31.690 --> 00:12:35.040
And candidly, the best
line ever, ever given

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:40.080
about the market was "frankly,
madam, I do not give a damn."

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:42.500
None of us should be paying
attention to the stock market

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:45.630
nearly as much as we pay
attention to ourselves.

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:50.670
If you know who you are, where
you are, where you want to go,

00:12:50.670 --> 00:12:53.190
you will do more good
for yourself than if

00:12:53.190 --> 00:12:59.160
all about the stock market,
partly because it'll disappear,

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:01.890
because markets are
very temporary and gone.

00:13:01.890 --> 00:13:06.290
But you really are important,
and the rest of it is details.

00:13:06.290 --> 00:13:09.410
And the specificity and the
intensity and excitement

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:12.210
of the details can
attract attention.

00:13:12.210 --> 00:13:15.930
But if you didn't know a
thing about what was going on,

00:13:15.930 --> 00:13:17.480
you could still
find your pathway

00:13:17.480 --> 00:13:21.180
through what's going to be
going on in the long run.

00:13:21.180 --> 00:13:23.230
I assume you've read Nate
Silver's wonderful book

00:13:23.230 --> 00:13:24.760
about "The Signal
and the Noise."

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:27.780
It's a terrific book, and
a terrifically smart guy

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:30.910
who's put together an awful lot
of insight and understanding.

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:32.190
He's right.

00:13:32.190 --> 00:13:35.470
The signal and the noise--
pay attention to the signal.

00:13:35.470 --> 00:13:37.440
Don't worry about the noise.

00:13:37.440 --> 00:13:41.050
And if the signal tunes in
for you in a particular way,

00:13:41.050 --> 00:13:42.960
or you can tune in
with it, you can

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:46.960
do some important value
adding decision making.

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:50.505
All the other things
are best ignored.

00:13:50.505 --> 00:13:51.880
BURTON MALKIEL:
And in fact, they

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:55.540
ought to be ignored, because
to the extent that they affect

00:13:55.540 --> 00:13:59.030
you, they make you
do the wrong thing.

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:00.225
One of the things--

00:14:00.225 --> 00:14:01.850
CHARLEY ELLIS: If
you're a human being.

00:14:01.850 --> 00:14:04.230
BURTON MALKIEL: And that's
where this new field

00:14:04.230 --> 00:14:06.990
of the behavioral
finance comes in.

00:14:10.300 --> 00:14:14.450
We have very good data
on the flow of money

00:14:14.450 --> 00:14:16.880
into equity mutual funds.

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:20.320
And what we know
is that money flows

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:22.550
in when everyone's optimistic.

00:14:22.550 --> 00:14:27.690
More money flowed into
equity mutual funds

00:14:27.690 --> 00:14:30.330
in the first
quarter of 2000 that

00:14:30.330 --> 00:14:33.910
happened to be the top of
the internet bubble than ever

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:35.080
before.

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:38.350
And then at the market bottom
in about the third quarter

00:14:38.350 --> 00:14:43.530
of 2002, the money went out,
then the money came back in.

00:14:43.530 --> 00:14:46.460
And more money
came out than ever

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:50.820
before in the third
quarter of 2008,

00:14:50.820 --> 00:14:53.870
at the height-- or
the depth, if you

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:57.110
wish-- of the financial
crisis, when everyone

00:14:57.110 --> 00:14:58.640
thought the world
was going to end.

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:01.600
So the problem with
looking at the noise

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:05.400
is it makes you do
the wrong thing.

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:08.710
You're selling when, if
anything, you should be buying.

00:15:08.710 --> 00:15:12.240
And you're buying when
everyone is very optimistic,

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:14.950
and if anything, you
should be careful.

00:15:14.950 --> 00:15:20.470
And that's the real
problem of letting

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:28.510
the noise effect you,
rather than simply if you're

00:15:28.510 --> 00:15:33.830
saving for trying to build
up a big retirement nest egg,

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:40.650
of just doing it to
evenly over time,

00:15:40.650 --> 00:15:43.030
take advantage of
the opportunities

00:15:43.030 --> 00:15:48.538
when the market's down, not
sell, but keep a study course.

00:15:48.538 --> 00:15:50.121
ADAM NASH: You know,
it's-- oh, sorry.

00:15:50.121 --> 00:15:50.360
Go ahead.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:51.110
CHARLEY ELLIS: All
three of us went

00:15:51.110 --> 00:15:52.000
to Harvard Business School.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:53.170
It was a great place to go.

00:15:53.170 --> 00:15:54.269
You can learn a lot.

00:15:54.269 --> 00:15:56.310
You can take the course
on investment management.

00:15:56.310 --> 00:15:57.360
You can learn a lot.

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:00.870
You'd learn more if you
could just take five years

00:16:00.870 --> 00:16:05.310
and be a parent of
a teenage child.

00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:07.560
You realize, it's very exciting.

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:08.570
It's very interesting.

00:16:08.570 --> 00:16:10.885
It really gets you excited
positively sometimes,

00:16:10.885 --> 00:16:13.300
and it gets you very excited
negatively sometimes.

00:16:13.300 --> 00:16:14.510
And it doesn't matter.

00:16:14.510 --> 00:16:18.460
They grow up to be
wonderful, long run.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:21.740
ADAM NASH: My teenage
years weren't so exciting,

00:16:21.740 --> 00:16:23.596
but I may have done it wrong.

00:16:23.596 --> 00:16:24.620
[LAUGHS]

00:16:24.620 --> 00:16:26.580
CHARLEY ELLIS: Depends--
exciting to you,

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:27.746
or exciting to your parents?

00:16:27.746 --> 00:16:29.580
ADAM NASH: I'm sure it
was exciting to them.

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:31.037
CHARLEY ELLIS: I
would have thought

00:16:31.037 --> 00:16:32.786
they'd have been
really deeply afraid.

00:16:32.786 --> 00:16:34.160
ADAM NASH: [LAUGHS]
They're still

00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:36.500
trying to figure out how
their son ended up in a career

00:16:36.500 --> 00:16:38.333
where he doesn't have
to dress up every day.

00:16:38.333 --> 00:16:39.650
CHARLEY ELLIS: Right.

00:16:39.650 --> 00:16:41.290
ADAM NASH: Actually,
I like this focus

00:16:41.290 --> 00:16:42.645
on long term and investing.

00:16:42.645 --> 00:16:43.520
I see a big parallel.

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:46.050
But great technology
companies have always

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:49.900
been the ones that got out of
the day-to-day quarter focus,

00:16:49.900 --> 00:16:53.360
even when public, and focused
on initiatives three, five,

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:54.400
10 years out.

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:56.180
I mean, Larry's done
that here at Google.

00:16:56.180 --> 00:16:59.460
I think Jeff has done that
fantastically well at Amazon.

00:16:59.460 --> 00:17:00.950
I think that it's rare.

00:17:00.950 --> 00:17:02.630
But the great
technology companies

00:17:02.630 --> 00:17:07.210
know that technology reinvents
the rules every few years,

00:17:07.210 --> 00:17:10.200
but it's fairly predictable
that scale will increase,

00:17:10.200 --> 00:17:14.361
speed will increase,
and what's now possible.

00:17:14.361 --> 00:17:15.819
So a lot of the
folks in this room,

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:17.040
their first job may
have been at Google,

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:19.500
or they may have been
other technology companies.

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:22.450
You were both
involved with Vanguard

00:17:22.450 --> 00:17:24.054
in the very earliest of days.

00:17:24.054 --> 00:17:25.720
And for most of the
people in this room,

00:17:25.720 --> 00:17:29.820
Vanguard is a huge fact of
the financial industry--

00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:32.480
trillions in
assets, index funds.

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:34.870
It's a staple of what
people think is available,

00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:36.260
but that wasn't always true.

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:38.770
Vanguard was effectively
a startup as well.

00:17:38.770 --> 00:17:40.685
Do you guys want to comment on--

00:17:40.685 --> 00:17:42.460
CHARLEY ELLIS: Well,
we differed on that.

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:46.650
Burt wisely said, "I
think this could work,"

00:17:46.650 --> 00:17:49.580
and worked with Jack
Bogle to make it go.

00:17:49.580 --> 00:17:54.510
And I unwisely went to
Jack and said, "Jack, you

00:17:54.510 --> 00:17:55.850
made a terrible mistake.

00:17:55.850 --> 00:17:58.350
You're in a short,
dead-end street.

00:17:58.350 --> 00:17:59.857
It's not going to work out.

00:17:59.857 --> 00:18:01.440
All of your friends
know you've really

00:18:01.440 --> 00:18:03.800
screwed up making
this commitment.

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:07.490
If you just stop now and come
back into the normal world,

00:18:07.490 --> 00:18:09.790
you'll be OK."

00:18:09.790 --> 00:18:13.127
Forgiveness is a part of the
investment management world.

00:18:13.127 --> 00:18:15.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:15.990 --> 00:18:18.332
CHARLEY ELLIS: On the
whole, Burt was dead right.

00:18:18.332 --> 00:18:20.730
On the whole, I was dead wrong.

00:18:20.730 --> 00:18:23.700
BURTON MALKIEL: But
you know, the fact is,

00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:27.570
when I first wrote my
"Random Walk" book, which

00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:31.110
is in all of these editions--
it was actually 1973--

00:18:31.110 --> 00:18:32.610
and it recommended
that people would

00:18:32.610 --> 00:18:34.940
be better off with index funds.

00:18:34.940 --> 00:18:38.920
And I had a market
professional review my book

00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:41.750
in "Business Week," as it was
the worst review I ever got.

00:18:41.750 --> 00:18:43.980
They said this is the
biggest piece of garbage

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:46.430
that they had ever seen.

00:18:46.430 --> 00:18:49.070
And when Jack started
the first index fund,

00:18:49.070 --> 00:18:51.390
it was called Bogle's Folly.

00:18:51.390 --> 00:18:55.460
And in fact, I sometimes like
to think that Jack and I were

00:18:55.460 --> 00:18:57.580
the only to investors
in the index fund.

00:18:57.580 --> 00:18:59.410
It was very slow to start.

00:18:59.410 --> 00:19:02.330
It wasn't that this just
took off right away.

00:19:02.330 --> 00:19:04.470
It didn't.

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:10.760
It was years and years before
it had any significant assets.

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:14.060
And again, that just shows
you the importance of,

00:19:14.060 --> 00:19:14.790
it was right.

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:21.670
People say, well, who
wants to be mediocre?

00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:23.080
It's not mediocre.

00:19:23.080 --> 00:19:30.730
It's being above average,
being in a low-cost index fund.

00:19:30.730 --> 00:19:34.710
And after a while, it
did start to take off.

00:19:34.710 --> 00:19:38.960
But believe me, it
was very, very slow.

00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:44.020
And people thought this was the
stupidest idea in the world.

00:19:44.020 --> 00:19:46.260
CHARLEY ELLIS: There were
advertisements taken out

00:19:46.260 --> 00:19:48.750
in a trade magazine.

00:19:48.750 --> 00:19:53.110
"Index funds are un-American."

00:19:53.110 --> 00:19:55.880
And it was run over and
over and over again,

00:19:55.880 --> 00:19:58.390
because it got the
laughs, but it also

00:19:58.390 --> 00:20:00.510
was what people really
felt emotionally.

00:20:03.362 --> 00:20:05.570
ADAM NASH: I think it's
seductive to believe that you

00:20:05.570 --> 00:20:08.285
can outsmart the market or
figure these things out.

00:20:08.285 --> 00:20:10.160
CHARLEY ELLIS: Well,
can I interrupt you just

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:10.460
for a second?

00:20:10.460 --> 00:20:10.950
ADAM NASH: Oh, yeah.

00:20:10.950 --> 00:20:13.241
CHARLEY ELLIS: If you're
trying to outsmart the market,

00:20:13.241 --> 00:20:15.840
that's self deception.

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:18.030
It's not as though the
market is out there

00:20:18.030 --> 00:20:20.460
doing whatever markets do.

00:20:20.460 --> 00:20:23.110
There's a smart son of a
bitch on the other side

00:20:23.110 --> 00:20:24.470
of every trade.

00:20:24.470 --> 00:20:26.650
And when we were
children and just getting

00:20:26.650 --> 00:20:33.800
started in investment management
50 years ago, 92%, 94%, 95%

00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:36.500
was done by
individual investors.

00:20:36.500 --> 00:20:37.750
What's an individual investor?

00:20:37.750 --> 00:20:40.324
Well, he makes a trade
every year and a half.

00:20:40.324 --> 00:20:41.240
Every year and a half?

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:42.550
One trade?

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:44.230
Why does he buy or sell?

00:20:44.230 --> 00:20:48.199
Well, he buys because he got
a bonus of a thousand dollars,

00:20:48.199 --> 00:20:50.240
or he sells because he
wants to help his daughter

00:20:50.240 --> 00:20:51.439
pay for college.

00:20:51.439 --> 00:20:53.230
It has nothing to do
with the stock market.

00:20:53.230 --> 00:20:56.120
He doesn't do any
comparison shopping.

00:20:56.120 --> 00:21:00.560
Half of them bought AT&amp;T,
and then half of the rest

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:02.645
bought the company
they worked for,

00:21:02.645 --> 00:21:05.000
and the rest bought some
company they'd heard about,

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:07.990
that must be a good company
because one of their friends

00:21:07.990 --> 00:21:10.490
told them about it.

00:21:10.490 --> 00:21:13.040
Honest to goodness, it's
not hard to beat people

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:16.040
who have no access to
information or research,

00:21:16.040 --> 00:21:19.160
have no comparison
value, aren't doing it

00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:21.186
with anything like
rigor analysis.

00:21:21.186 --> 00:21:22.686
They just kind,
well, I've got some.

00:21:22.686 --> 00:21:25.470
Why don't I buy some.

00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:29.900
Today, it's not 95%
done by individuals.

00:21:29.900 --> 00:21:33.790
It's 96% done by experts.

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:39.930
48 of the 96 are done by the 50
largest, most active investors.

00:21:39.930 --> 00:21:42.150
These are people
that really care.

00:21:42.150 --> 00:21:43.920
And they've got
terrific equipment.

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:46.330
They've all got it-- at
least a couple Bloombergs,

00:21:46.330 --> 00:21:49.050
usually have one at
home, one at the office.

00:21:49.050 --> 00:21:52.050
They've got tremendous access
to factual information.

00:21:52.050 --> 00:21:54.190
Everybody gives
them the first call.

00:21:54.190 --> 00:21:56.480
Everybody wants to do
business with them.

00:21:56.480 --> 00:21:59.360
They are so actively in the
market so much of the time,

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:03.350
and they've spent years
mastering the industry

00:22:03.350 --> 00:22:04.900
that they're working in.

00:22:04.900 --> 00:22:09.956
And when they get you
in the crosshairs--

00:22:09.956 --> 00:22:11.830
it was all well and good
when George Plimpton

00:22:11.830 --> 00:22:14.522
would go out and play
against the NFL team.

00:22:14.522 --> 00:22:17.160
But personally, if
I were to go out,

00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:18.750
that would be the
way I would be.

00:22:18.750 --> 00:22:22.151
I'd be absolute bait
for destruction.

00:22:22.151 --> 00:22:23.900
And the same thing is
in the stock market.

00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:26.890
If you take on these
guys, they're really good.

00:22:26.890 --> 00:22:28.030
And they're killers.

00:22:28.030 --> 00:22:29.922
ADAM NASH: It's ironic
that a good, low-cost,

00:22:29.922 --> 00:22:30.880
diversified portfolio--

00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:31.160
CHARLEY ELLIS: Wait a minute.

00:22:31.160 --> 00:22:32.240
Let me give you the punch line.

00:22:32.240 --> 00:22:33.531
You don't have to take them on.

00:22:33.531 --> 00:22:37.970
You can let them do all
the work, all the work,

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:39.370
and the rest is on automatic.

00:22:39.370 --> 00:22:42.130
And that's basically what
index funds are all about.

00:22:42.130 --> 00:22:44.505
After they've figured out
what the prices ought to be--

00:22:44.505 --> 00:22:46.380
and there's a lot of
work on price discovery,

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:48.546
and they get really good
at discovering the prices--

00:22:48.546 --> 00:22:50.796
once they've figured
it out, say fine.

00:22:50.796 --> 00:22:51.920
I'll take what they've got.

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:53.590
I'll have what she's having.

00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:55.200
ADAM NASH: Well,
you know, what's

00:22:55.200 --> 00:22:59.730
fascinated me is Wealthfront,
our average customer right now

00:22:59.730 --> 00:23:00.400
is in their 30s.

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:02.270
A lot of twentysomethings,
thirtysomethings,

00:23:02.270 --> 00:23:06.800
fortysomethings, they
tend to be more technical.

00:23:06.800 --> 00:23:09.190
And they've been through
these two market crashes,

00:23:09.190 --> 00:23:11.560
so the thing that I
hear over and over again

00:23:11.560 --> 00:23:13.310
from folks-- I like
to talk to customers--

00:23:13.310 --> 00:23:15.300
is that they don't
think they're going

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:17.090
to make their money
by beating the market.

00:23:17.090 --> 00:23:19.298
They think they're going to
make their money by being

00:23:19.298 --> 00:23:22.870
a great engineer or a great
designer or building a company.

00:23:22.870 --> 00:23:25.890
They just want to have
their money soundly invested

00:23:25.890 --> 00:23:27.700
in a low-cost way.

00:23:27.700 --> 00:23:29.345
When you folks talk
to young people

00:23:29.345 --> 00:23:30.720
now-- I know you're
both involved

00:23:30.720 --> 00:23:34.910
a lot with different groups
and teaching-- how do you give

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:38.760
advice to folks in Gen Y,
Gen X, young people who

00:23:38.760 --> 00:23:42.780
are at early stages
in their career?

00:23:42.780 --> 00:23:45.500
BURTON MALKIEL:
Well, I generally

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:52.980
tell them to put money
into their investments

00:23:52.980 --> 00:24:00.560
regularly over time, no matter
what is happening, and don't

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:04.860
worry if the stock
market goes down.

00:24:04.860 --> 00:24:10.040
There's probably one
of these professionals

00:24:10.040 --> 00:24:13.710
that Charley's talking about,
and maybe the best investor

00:24:13.710 --> 00:24:15.970
that we've got in the
country, is Warren Buffett.

00:24:15.970 --> 00:24:24.560
And he has a wonderful
essay which says,

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:29.130
suppose you love
hamburgers, and that you're

00:24:29.130 --> 00:24:33.300
going to be eating
hamburgers all your life,

00:24:33.300 --> 00:24:36.460
and you're not a cattle rancher.

00:24:36.460 --> 00:24:38.790
Would you like the
price of hamburgers

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:40.267
to go up or down in the future?

00:24:40.267 --> 00:24:42.475
You say, well, OK, I'm going
to be buying hamburgers.

00:24:42.475 --> 00:24:46.220
Let's just assume the
hamburgers I buy next week

00:24:46.220 --> 00:24:47.935
and next year are lower.

00:24:47.935 --> 00:24:49.990
You say OK, you
got that one right.

00:24:49.990 --> 00:24:53.016
OK, here's the second
part of the quiz.

00:24:53.016 --> 00:24:54.890
Suppose you're going to
be buying automobiles

00:24:54.890 --> 00:24:58.340
all your life, and you're not
an automobile manufacturer.

00:24:58.340 --> 00:25:03.010
Do you want the price of
automobiles to go up or down?

00:25:03.010 --> 00:25:06.990
You say, well, I'd just assume
the next auto I buy is actually

00:25:06.990 --> 00:25:09.200
cheaper than the
one I just bought.

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:10.610
And Buffet says, good.

00:25:10.610 --> 00:25:12.670
You got that one right too.

00:25:12.670 --> 00:25:16.180
Now, for the final
exam, suppose you're

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:20.030
going to be investing
all your life.

00:25:20.030 --> 00:25:27.550
You're going to be putting
money aside all your life.

00:25:27.550 --> 00:25:30.070
Do you want the stock
market to go up or down?

00:25:30.070 --> 00:25:32.910
And Buffett says this is
where people generally

00:25:32.910 --> 00:25:36.280
flunk the final exam.

00:25:36.280 --> 00:25:39.490
It's only if you're in
retirement and taking money out

00:25:39.490 --> 00:25:42.350
that you want the stock
prices to be high.

00:25:42.350 --> 00:25:44.947
It's as if you're asking that
the hamburgers that you're

00:25:44.947 --> 00:25:47.530
going to be buying and the cars
that you're going to be buying

00:25:47.530 --> 00:25:49.250
are going to go up in price.

00:25:49.250 --> 00:25:55.070
In fact, through something
that's-- actually,

00:25:55.070 --> 00:25:58.860
the technical term for it
is dollar cost averaging--

00:25:58.860 --> 00:26:02.050
if, in fact, the
price goes down,

00:26:02.050 --> 00:26:03.660
your money goes even further.

00:26:03.660 --> 00:26:05.960
You can buy more shares.

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:10.150
And you can put a
little example down

00:26:10.150 --> 00:26:14.380
of how even when the
market is very volatile

00:26:14.380 --> 00:26:18.370
and doesn't go up at
all, you can make money

00:26:18.370 --> 00:26:23.300
because you bought more shares
when the market was down.

00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:25.930
And one of the
simulations that I've done

00:26:25.930 --> 00:26:31.430
is take a decade-- the first
decade of the 2000s, which

00:26:31.430 --> 00:26:34.770
has been called by investors
"the lost decade," because

00:26:34.770 --> 00:26:38.880
in general, if you put
money in the S&amp;P 500

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:43.440
on January 1 of 2000
and looked at what

00:26:43.440 --> 00:26:47.250
it was worth on
December 31 of 2009,

00:26:47.250 --> 00:26:49.290
you didn't make any money.

00:26:49.290 --> 00:26:51.660
The second decade's
been pretty good,

00:26:51.660 --> 00:26:53.870
but the first
decade was terrible.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:58.050
But if you put money in
every quarter, regularly,

00:26:58.050 --> 00:27:00.500
you actually made a
pretty good rate of return

00:27:00.500 --> 00:27:02.500
even during the lost decade.

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:07.940
So what I try to tell
people is, generally,

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:12.020
put the money in steadily.

00:27:12.020 --> 00:27:14.690
Nobody can time the market.

00:27:14.690 --> 00:27:16.530
Professionals can't do it.

00:27:16.530 --> 00:27:18.990
Look, I've been in
this game for 50 years.

00:27:18.990 --> 00:27:21.640
I've never known anyone
who can time the market.

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:23.260
I've never known
anyone who knows

00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:25.330
anyone who can time the market.

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:28.740
It's not that the efficient
market hypothesis means

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:31.640
that prices are always
right, and that's

00:27:31.640 --> 00:27:34.300
how some people
poo-poo the idea.

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:35.820
Prices are not always right.

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:37.040
They're always wrong.

00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:39.410
The problem is, no
one knows for sure

00:27:39.410 --> 00:27:42.744
whether they're too
high or too low.

00:27:42.744 --> 00:27:44.410
ADAM NASH: What I
love about that advice

00:27:44.410 --> 00:27:48.463
is it highlights actually
good financial fundamentals.

00:27:48.463 --> 00:27:50.462
It turns out the most
important for young people

00:27:50.462 --> 00:27:52.920
is just to be saving, they
save regularly, and put

00:27:52.920 --> 00:27:53.930
in the market.

00:27:53.930 --> 00:27:57.060
It's actually better for them
if the market has up and down,

00:27:57.060 --> 00:27:59.050
because they'll get
some of the downs.

00:27:59.050 --> 00:28:01.300
True, you get some of the
ups, but the long-term trend

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:03.840
is obviously their friend.

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:04.564
Sorry, go ahead.

00:28:04.564 --> 00:28:06.980
CHARLEY ELLIS: You just said
it, but saving is number one.

00:28:06.980 --> 00:28:07.972
ADAM NASH: Yes.

00:28:07.972 --> 00:28:09.430
CHARLEY ELLIS: Not
getting excited,

00:28:09.430 --> 00:28:14.150
either at the top or the
bottom, is number two.

00:28:14.150 --> 00:28:18.050
And then regular
investing, ho-hum,

00:28:18.050 --> 00:28:20.740
steady, steady,
steady-- number three.

00:28:20.740 --> 00:28:23.450
And it works out fabulously.

00:28:23.450 --> 00:28:26.236
But it takes some
self discipline when

00:28:26.236 --> 00:28:28.110
the excitement around
you, and all the people

00:28:28.110 --> 00:28:30.100
are talking in the
newspapers and magazines

00:28:30.100 --> 00:28:31.850
and television programs
are talking about,

00:28:31.850 --> 00:28:33.740
this may be the last
chance to get in

00:28:33.740 --> 00:28:35.930
on a wonderful opportunity.

00:28:35.930 --> 00:28:38.660
It's very hard not to
get deeply concerned when

00:28:38.660 --> 00:28:41.640
you see the whole
economy's falling apart,

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:43.830
Asia's going wrong,
Europe's going wrong,

00:28:43.830 --> 00:28:45.810
the president's having
a terrible time,

00:28:45.810 --> 00:28:48.810
the president's wife
is unhappy with him,

00:28:48.810 --> 00:28:51.430
your wife is unhappy with
you, and your friends are all

00:28:51.430 --> 00:28:53.960
deeply concerned, and the
food doesn't taste good.

00:28:53.960 --> 00:28:55.942
It's pretty hard not
to get depressed.

00:28:55.942 --> 00:28:57.900
But you've got to hang
in there, because that's

00:28:57.900 --> 00:29:00.470
the time of your best
chance of your lifetime.

00:29:00.470 --> 00:29:04.990
BURTON MALKIEL: And control the
things that you can control.

00:29:04.990 --> 00:29:08.260
You can't control the ups
and downs of the market.

00:29:08.260 --> 00:29:10.970
You can control your costs.

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:16.700
You can control your
taxes that you pay.

00:29:16.700 --> 00:29:21.580
And you can use the best friend
you've got for reducing risk,

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:23.750
and that's diversifying.

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:28.560
So diversify, control the
things that you can control,

00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:32.190
and as much as the
market might fluctuate,

00:29:32.190 --> 00:29:33.690
don't worry about it.

00:29:33.690 --> 00:29:34.952
You'll come out OK.

00:29:34.952 --> 00:29:37.967
ADAM NASH: You know, I
think it's such good advice.

00:29:37.967 --> 00:29:39.550
Ironically I think
in some ways, we've

00:29:39.550 --> 00:29:43.440
made it harder on ourselves
in this generation.

00:29:43.440 --> 00:29:45.090
We all have smartphones
in our pockets.

00:29:45.090 --> 00:29:46.200
They buzz all the time.

00:29:46.200 --> 00:29:49.710
We're checking our feeds,
whether it's Google+ Facebook

00:29:49.710 --> 00:29:50.210
or Twitter.

00:29:50.210 --> 00:29:52.990
There's this stuff
happening all the time.

00:29:52.990 --> 00:29:55.971
So learning that
basic fact that,

00:29:55.971 --> 00:29:57.720
that there are some
things you can control

00:29:57.720 --> 00:30:00.240
and some things you
can't, is really

00:30:00.240 --> 00:30:02.240
important with investing.

00:30:02.240 --> 00:30:04.660
CHARLEY ELLIS: One thing,
just an easy metric on this,

00:30:04.660 --> 00:30:07.940
is don't never do
nothing that you're not

00:30:07.940 --> 00:30:11.860
prepared to hold onto for at
least 10 years, whatever it is.

00:30:11.860 --> 00:30:14.940
ADAM NASH: 10 years.

00:30:14.940 --> 00:30:16.780
I mean, actually
it's a good segue.

00:30:16.780 --> 00:30:20.510
You did an interview, I
think, recently, with--

00:30:20.510 --> 00:30:21.677
was it "Investor News," or--

00:30:21.677 --> 00:30:23.343
CHARLEY ELLIS:
"Institutional Investor."

00:30:23.343 --> 00:30:25.170
ADAM NASH:
"Institutional Investor."

00:30:25.170 --> 00:30:29.000
I think of the title the
article was "Is Alpha Dead?"

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:32.260
And I mean, compared
to 40 years ago,

00:30:32.260 --> 00:30:35.207
do you feel like-- is it the
same as it's always been,

00:30:35.207 --> 00:30:38.994
or has it got even harder
to beat the market?

00:30:38.994 --> 00:30:40.910
CHARLEY ELLIS: 50 years
ago, it was relatively

00:30:40.910 --> 00:30:44.140
easy to do better than
the market rate of return,

00:30:44.140 --> 00:30:47.840
because the competition
wasn't very good.

00:30:47.840 --> 00:30:52.450
Today, the competition
is just marvelous.

00:30:52.450 --> 00:30:54.280
Every time you buy,
you buy from somebody

00:30:54.280 --> 00:30:55.910
who knows a hell
of a lot about it.

00:30:55.910 --> 00:30:57.451
Every time you sell
something, you're

00:30:57.451 --> 00:31:00.090
selling it to somebody who
knows a hell of a lot about it.

00:31:00.090 --> 00:31:02.820
They may make mistakes,
but how smart are you

00:31:02.820 --> 00:31:05.300
that you won't have made at
least about the same the number

00:31:05.300 --> 00:31:10.610
of mistakes, plus the cost of
being there in the activity?

00:31:10.610 --> 00:31:13.320
It's just, the
world has changed.

00:31:13.320 --> 00:31:16.670
And McCain said, one
wonderful sentence,

00:31:16.670 --> 00:31:18.880
"When the facts change,
I change my mind.

00:31:18.880 --> 00:31:20.990
What do you do about yours?"

00:31:20.990 --> 00:31:22.680
And it's worth thinking about.

00:31:22.680 --> 00:31:25.530
And the world of
investing has changed.

00:31:25.530 --> 00:31:28.570
And so what would be
sensible 50 years ago

00:31:28.570 --> 00:31:31.600
could now be not
at all sensible.

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:33.240
All the evidence
is that it doesn't

00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:37.490
work to do what would
have worked 50 years ago.

00:31:37.490 --> 00:31:39.290
Fine.

00:31:39.290 --> 00:31:44.430
ADAM NASH: Well, I think
it's magical in some ways

00:31:44.430 --> 00:31:47.330
that we've evolved the industry
to the point where you can own

00:31:47.330 --> 00:31:50.240
the entire US stock market for
such an incredibly cheap rate.

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:54.214
I mean, five basis points
is kind of amazing.

00:31:54.214 --> 00:31:56.380
It's good to know that even
in this arms race that's

00:31:56.380 --> 00:31:58.296
going on amongst the
professional investor set

00:31:58.296 --> 00:32:00.790
that you can do better
than most of them

00:32:00.790 --> 00:32:04.270
just by buying the
simple index funds.

00:32:04.270 --> 00:32:07.790
Let me segue a bit, some
kind of topical news.

00:32:07.790 --> 00:32:11.860
The Federal Reserve has been
in the news a lot lately.

00:32:11.860 --> 00:32:15.850
Both of you have had careers--
you worked with Alan Greenspan

00:32:15.850 --> 00:32:20.940
at one point, Ben Bernanke,
I think even Janet Yellen,

00:32:20.940 --> 00:32:23.900
we were talking about.

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:27.430
Any comments about
what the differences

00:32:27.430 --> 00:32:32.260
are, what it takes to be a
great Federal Reserve chairman?

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:35.105
I mean, it's something you
going to really look over

00:32:35.105 --> 00:32:35.990
over decades.

00:32:35.990 --> 00:32:38.110
It's not something you
can really understand just

00:32:38.110 --> 00:32:40.085
looking at the most
recent candidates.

00:32:40.085 --> 00:32:40.730
CHARLEY ELLIS: Oh,
I think there's

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:41.910
some things you could say.

00:32:41.910 --> 00:32:46.450
Number one, Federal Reserve
governance is a team sport.

00:32:46.450 --> 00:32:49.760
So if you are not really good
at working with other people,

00:32:49.760 --> 00:32:51.510
you've got a real problem.

00:32:51.510 --> 00:32:53.260
Secondly, I think
you could easily

00:32:53.260 --> 00:32:56.450
say we have been really
fortunate to have

00:32:56.450 --> 00:32:58.260
some extraordinary
people serving

00:32:58.260 --> 00:33:02.522
in the governorship, but
particularly the chairman.

00:33:02.522 --> 00:33:03.980
You should talk
about Ben Bernanke,

00:33:03.980 --> 00:33:05.771
because you really
worked closely with him.

00:33:05.771 --> 00:33:11.550
I knew him, but-- I knew Janet
Yellen quite closely at Yale.

00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:13.640
These are extraordinary
people who

00:33:13.640 --> 00:33:16.410
have studied and studied and
studied the field in which they

00:33:16.410 --> 00:33:18.010
are then put to test.

00:33:18.010 --> 00:33:22.290
Everything that they live
with is new, difficult,

00:33:22.290 --> 00:33:26.040
fast moving, and the
data is not available.

00:33:26.040 --> 00:33:28.330
So it's a really tough job.

00:33:28.330 --> 00:33:30.880
But if you wanted
to pick people who

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:33.290
are wonderfully
well-suited to that,

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:35.650
out of all the people
that might be chosen,

00:33:35.650 --> 00:33:38.210
we've been very, very
fortune as a nation.

00:33:38.210 --> 00:33:41.380
And what's wonderful is
that the rest of the world

00:33:41.380 --> 00:33:44.461
has very talented people in
their central banks also,

00:33:44.461 --> 00:33:46.710
but that these people talk
to each other all the time.

00:33:46.710 --> 00:33:48.140
And the factual
information that's

00:33:48.140 --> 00:33:50.710
accessible to the
bankers is terrific.

00:33:50.710 --> 00:33:51.430
Is it perfect?

00:33:51.430 --> 00:33:52.490
Certainly not.

00:33:52.490 --> 00:33:53.310
Is it a hard job?

00:33:53.310 --> 00:33:54.560
You bet.

00:33:54.560 --> 00:33:57.970
An unwinding of this massive
purchase of mortgages

00:33:57.970 --> 00:34:00.780
is going to be an
unbelievably challenging--

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:01.950
when do you do it?

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:02.990
How do you do it?

00:34:02.990 --> 00:34:04.690
How do you communicate about it?

00:34:04.690 --> 00:34:06.281
It's going to be hard.

00:34:06.281 --> 00:34:08.239
BURTON MALKIEL: I would
agree with you, surely,

00:34:08.239 --> 00:34:11.770
that the consensus
building is so important.

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:20.510
And Ben came from my university,
and so I've seen Ben in action.

00:34:20.510 --> 00:34:25.540
Herding a group of
prima donna faculty

00:34:25.540 --> 00:34:31.389
around is not one of the
easiest things in the world,

00:34:31.389 --> 00:34:34.940
and Ben was a brilliant
department chairman.

00:34:34.940 --> 00:34:37.480
And I think Ben
was quite brilliant

00:34:37.480 --> 00:34:39.389
as the leader of
the Federal Reserve.

00:34:39.389 --> 00:34:42.530
And I think one
of the things that

00:34:42.530 --> 00:34:46.190
is very likely to be the
case for Janet Yellen

00:34:46.190 --> 00:34:49.030
is that she has some
of the same qualities.

00:34:49.030 --> 00:34:59.620
So I agree with you that we've
got a big enough government

00:34:59.620 --> 00:35:05.690
portfolio that there are really
some questions about whether we

00:35:05.690 --> 00:35:10.920
have done something
to hurt the market.

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:14.030
Unwinding this,
which is certainly

00:35:14.030 --> 00:35:15.900
something that
needs to be done, is

00:35:15.900 --> 00:35:18.370
going to be very, very tricky.

00:35:18.370 --> 00:35:24.732
But I think we've got the
right people on board to do it.

00:35:24.732 --> 00:35:26.940
ADAM NASH: That's good to
hear. [LAUGHS] A little bit

00:35:26.940 --> 00:35:28.820
of good news.

00:35:28.820 --> 00:35:31.557
Before we open it
up to questions,

00:35:31.557 --> 00:35:33.390
because I know people
must have quite a few,

00:35:33.390 --> 00:35:36.290
I wanted to make sure to
ask a fundamental one.

00:35:36.290 --> 00:35:41.470
You've both been a part of some
very fundamental improvements

00:35:41.470 --> 00:35:45.770
in the structure of the
industry-- what clients deserve

00:35:45.770 --> 00:35:50.580
from their advisors, index
funds, passive investing-- I

00:35:50.580 --> 00:35:53.410
mean, just a wide
range of advocacy

00:35:53.410 --> 00:35:57.360
for making investing
better for individuals.

00:35:57.360 --> 00:36:00.070
How do you think
about your legacy,

00:36:00.070 --> 00:36:03.334
or what you want to make
sure continues going forward,

00:36:03.334 --> 00:36:04.750
given the progress
that we've been

00:36:04.750 --> 00:36:06.790
able to make over
the last few decades?

00:36:06.790 --> 00:36:08.415
BURTON MALKIEL: Well,
one of the things

00:36:08.415 --> 00:36:12.390
that I have the
worked on recently

00:36:12.390 --> 00:36:18.110
is to try to see if we could get
the whole industry to sign onto

00:36:18.110 --> 00:36:21.640
something that's called
the fiduciary standard.

00:36:21.640 --> 00:36:25.380
And it's sort of very simple--
that you don't do anything

00:36:25.380 --> 00:36:30.470
for your client that
you're not absolutely 100%

00:36:30.470 --> 00:36:34.240
convinced is in your
client's interest.

00:36:34.240 --> 00:36:36.190
And that's basically
what I think

00:36:36.190 --> 00:36:40.370
is the fundamental
problem with the industry,

00:36:40.370 --> 00:36:45.390
that there is this severe
conflict of interest.

00:36:45.390 --> 00:36:47.010
I mean, this is one
of the things that

00:36:47.010 --> 00:36:50.220
happened in the
financial crisis.

00:36:50.220 --> 00:36:57.710
If you are making a
lot of money selling

00:36:57.710 --> 00:37:00.890
mortgage-backed
securities, well, we're

00:37:00.890 --> 00:37:05.090
not going to worry what kind
of toxic stuff is in there.

00:37:05.090 --> 00:37:07.750
If people want to buy
it, let them buy it.

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:12.790
That was basically
what the industry did.

00:37:12.790 --> 00:37:17.870
And I think what
is the answer is,

00:37:17.870 --> 00:37:21.800
what informs every decision
you make is not whether it's

00:37:21.800 --> 00:37:29.630
good for me, whether it's going
to be good for my bottom line,

00:37:29.630 --> 00:37:33.030
but whether it is good for
the bottom line of the people

00:37:33.030 --> 00:37:33.880
we're serving.

00:37:33.880 --> 00:37:39.190
And if I had a
legacy that I wanted

00:37:39.190 --> 00:37:43.970
to leave on my tombstone,
that would be it.

00:37:43.970 --> 00:37:45.619
ADAM NASH: Charley?

00:37:45.619 --> 00:37:47.327
CHARLEY ELLIS: I don't
believe in legacy.

00:37:47.327 --> 00:37:51.025
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:51.025 --> 00:37:52.525
CHARLEY ELLIS: I
would just say read

00:37:52.525 --> 00:37:53.940
what Burt wrote
on his tombstone.

00:37:53.940 --> 00:37:54.620
That'd do fine.

00:37:57.690 --> 00:38:00.280
It's a cultural problem.

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:02.570
If we get enough
misbehaving, we'll

00:38:02.570 --> 00:38:05.260
get enough correctives
so that the culture will

00:38:05.260 --> 00:38:07.720
move towards doing the
right sorts of things.

00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:10.500
But once you separate
the professional value

00:38:10.500 --> 00:38:13.430
from the economics
of the business,

00:38:13.430 --> 00:38:16.250
the business economics are
going to take off and get

00:38:16.250 --> 00:38:17.130
to be dominant.

00:38:17.130 --> 00:38:19.370
And it will attract
people who say, well, you

00:38:19.370 --> 00:38:21.411
get pretty good pay over there.

00:38:21.411 --> 00:38:23.160
It doesn't look like
all that boring work,

00:38:23.160 --> 00:38:26.510
so I'd like to do it,
and that recreates.

00:38:26.510 --> 00:38:31.180
If you go back and read
economic history in the '30s,

00:38:31.180 --> 00:38:34.490
there were some marvelous
hearings in Washington

00:38:34.490 --> 00:38:37.670
where one banker after another
was embarrassed something

00:38:37.670 --> 00:38:41.080
unbelievable to be asked
a series of questions--

00:38:41.080 --> 00:38:42.330
the Pujo hearings.

00:38:42.330 --> 00:38:45.360
And it's kind of fun
to read back over that.

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:50.290
It's just so similar
to what we did.

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:57.100
In the last round-- 2008,
and the break in the market--

00:38:57.100 --> 00:39:00.310
you can trace an
unfortunately large fraction

00:39:00.310 --> 00:39:02.250
of the really
severe difficulties

00:39:02.250 --> 00:39:07.480
to very specific
individuals who misbehaved.

00:39:07.480 --> 00:39:09.760
And it wasn't the
people down the line

00:39:09.760 --> 00:39:10.910
that did the worst of it.

00:39:10.910 --> 00:39:14.070
It was the people at the
top of those organizations

00:39:14.070 --> 00:39:21.220
that did the worst of
it, and that's a shame.

