and it just happened to be
that instead of doing better

00:39:44.600 --> 00:39:47.060
than the market, they happened
to do slightly less well,

00:39:47.060 --> 00:39:49.260
but they've done some
wonderful things to improve,

00:39:49.260 --> 00:39:52.770
and they're going to be able to
do to terrific in the future.

00:39:52.770 --> 00:39:57.960
And I'm looking at the numbers,
and I realized-- never actually

00:39:57.960 --> 00:40:01.700
realized it after
40 some odd years,

00:40:01.700 --> 00:40:07.300
48 years-- I hadn't
realized what the fees are.

00:40:07.300 --> 00:40:08.720
Now, most of us
in this room would

00:40:08.720 --> 00:40:11.770
be able to say,
oh, fees are small.

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:13.450
Fees are really small.

00:40:13.450 --> 00:40:16.530
It's usually a four-letter
word and a single number.

00:40:16.530 --> 00:40:20.810
"Only" is the four-letter word,
and 1% is the single number.

00:40:20.810 --> 00:40:22.860
Well, the 1% is not accurate.

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:28.210
Mutual funds typically
run closer to 1 and 1/4%

00:40:28.210 --> 00:40:30.249
of the assets.

00:40:30.249 --> 00:40:32.290
But then I would turn to
Burt and say, "but Burt,

00:40:32.290 --> 00:40:34.630
you've already got the assets."

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:39.227
So the fee isn't what you're
paying for what you're getting,

00:40:39.227 --> 00:40:40.810
because you've already
got the assets.

00:40:40.810 --> 00:40:41.910
What are you getting?

00:40:41.910 --> 00:40:44.410
Oh, Charley, we're
getting a return.

00:40:44.410 --> 00:40:45.690
Great.

00:40:45.690 --> 00:40:48.100
Normal expectation
of returns here,

00:40:48.100 --> 00:40:50.990
given the market's gone up a
fair amount, going forward,

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:54.720
might be 7% or 8%,
on average, with lots

00:40:54.720 --> 00:40:56.530
of ups and downs in between.

00:40:56.530 --> 00:41:00.490
So that 1%, or a little
over 1%-- as a percent,

00:41:00.490 --> 00:41:03.126
not of assets, but a
percent of the returns--

00:41:03.126 --> 00:41:04.250
what's that work out to be?

00:41:04.250 --> 00:41:06.480
Oh, let me do the math.

00:41:06.480 --> 00:41:08.919
Well, call it 15%.

00:41:08.919 --> 00:41:10.210
That doesn't sound like "only."

00:41:10.210 --> 00:41:11.000
I guess not.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.490
I guess that's really
actually pretty high.

00:41:13.490 --> 00:41:16.510
And then when I was in
school studying economics,

00:41:16.510 --> 00:41:20.300
we all were taught everything
is comparative price.

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:23.350
So what's the commodity product
and the commodity price?

00:41:23.350 --> 00:41:26.180
And then what's the custom
product and the custom price?

00:41:26.180 --> 00:41:29.060
The commodity product
is an index fund.

00:41:29.060 --> 00:41:31.660
It gets you the market
rate of return every day,

00:41:31.660 --> 00:41:35.780
every week, every month, every
year, same old, same old market

00:41:35.780 --> 00:41:39.080
rate of return, at no more,
no less than the market

00:41:39.080 --> 00:41:41.609
level or riskiness.

00:41:41.609 --> 00:41:43.400
OK, that's a pretty
good commodity product.

00:41:43.400 --> 00:41:44.680
What's it cost?

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:47.260
One-tenth of one percent.

00:41:47.260 --> 00:41:50.110
Now, you can get a
custom-tailored product,

00:41:50.110 --> 00:41:53.160
and what does it cost?

00:41:53.160 --> 00:41:57.850
Well, it costs-- if it's
10 basis points for one,

00:41:57.850 --> 00:42:00.600
it's 120 basis
points for the other.

00:42:00.600 --> 00:42:04.674
So incremental cost
is 110 basis points.

00:42:04.674 --> 00:42:07.090
Gee, I must get a pretty good
return in exchange for that,

00:42:07.090 --> 00:42:07.630
don't I?

00:42:07.630 --> 00:42:08.510
No, Charley.

00:42:08.510 --> 00:42:10.250
I'm sorry, but you don't.

00:42:10.250 --> 00:42:12.032
Actually, you get more risk.

00:42:12.032 --> 00:42:13.990
You get a lot of uncertainty,
because you never

00:42:13.990 --> 00:42:15.948
know when something's
really going to go wrong.

00:42:15.948 --> 00:42:18.360
But leave that
aside-- more risk,

00:42:18.360 --> 00:42:23.890
and on average, 3/4 of the
funds that are actively

00:42:23.890 --> 00:42:25.740
managed-- maybe it's
80% of the funds,

00:42:25.740 --> 00:42:28.580
somewhere in there--
underperform the benchmark

00:42:28.580 --> 00:42:30.790
that they said they
were going to match.

00:42:30.790 --> 00:42:32.680
And you never can
figure out who's

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:36.274
going to underperform--
most-- and you could never

00:42:36.274 --> 00:42:37.815
figure out who's
going to outperform.

00:42:40.790 --> 00:42:42.290
There's no way of doing it.

00:42:42.290 --> 00:42:44.930
So what you're doing when you
get a custom-tailored product

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:47.780
is you're paying
a much higher fee

00:42:47.780 --> 00:42:52.460
for less quality
and a lower return.

00:42:52.460 --> 00:42:54.320
And it is just
amazing that that's

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:58.220
something that continues
year after year after year.

00:42:58.220 --> 00:43:00.639
And it can't last for long,
but really smart people

00:43:00.639 --> 00:43:03.180
are going to figure it out and
say, I'm not going to do that.

00:43:03.180 --> 00:43:06.790
I'm going to take the
commodity product because it's

00:43:06.790 --> 00:43:11.540
cheaper and better return,
and I've got better things

00:43:11.540 --> 00:43:14.320
to do with my time than chewing
my nails over whether I'm

00:43:14.320 --> 00:43:16.131
going to be OK or not OK.

00:43:16.131 --> 00:43:18.630
BURTON MALKIEL: Let me just put
a footnote on this, Charley,

00:43:18.630 --> 00:43:23.190
because I've just done
some work on 401(k) plans.

00:43:23.190 --> 00:43:28.430
And in general, the cost
is more like 2% than 1%,

00:43:28.430 --> 00:43:32.400
because then there's a rep fee
around the high-priced mutual

00:43:32.400 --> 00:43:34.030
funds that are in there.

00:43:34.030 --> 00:43:39.760
And so you might say, instead
of getting a 7% return,

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:41.920
you get only a 5% return.

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:45.630
So your way of looking
at it is, it's not 2%.

00:43:45.630 --> 00:43:50.370
It's really 2/7 is
what you're paying.

00:43:50.370 --> 00:43:56.360
But it's even worse than that,
because these costs compound.

00:43:56.360 --> 00:44:02.520
If you think of putting
money in at 7% for 40 years

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:06.330
or putting money in
at 5% for 40 years,

00:44:06.330 --> 00:44:11.580
that difference at the
end isn't even 2/7.

00:44:11.580 --> 00:44:14.240
You're getting about half
the amount at the end,

00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:17.720
because the tyranny of the
compounding of the costs

00:44:17.720 --> 00:44:18.580
gets you.

00:44:18.580 --> 00:44:23.220
So again, it is
just so important,

00:44:23.220 --> 00:44:26.670
if you got something for
it, fine, but you don't.

00:44:26.670 --> 00:44:30.350
The evidence is
unmistakable that you don't.

00:44:30.350 --> 00:44:33.700
It's getting tougher and
tougher all the time.

00:44:33.700 --> 00:44:37.440
The market's not
always right, but there

00:44:37.440 --> 00:44:38.760
are few Warren Buffetts.

00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:42.460
I sometimes say if
when I wrote my book,

00:44:42.460 --> 00:44:45.270
I knew that Warren Buffett was
going to be Warren Buffett,

00:44:45.270 --> 00:44:47.252
I wouldn't have said
"buy an index fund."

00:44:47.252 --> 00:44:49.460
I would have said, "go buy
Berkshire Hathaway," which

00:44:49.460 --> 00:44:51.790
