got the best future,

00:53:22.280 --> 00:53:26.360
and I'd like to shifts my focus.

00:53:26.360 --> 00:53:30.180
And I'm curious how you see
that sort of reallocation.

00:53:30.180 --> 00:53:33.320
Like, what's the right
way to reallocate, or even

00:53:33.320 --> 00:53:36.640
to do it at all, because
there's this element of,

00:53:36.640 --> 00:53:38.210
well, you shouldn't
think about that.

00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:39.930
You should just keep
plodding forward.

00:53:39.930 --> 00:53:42.221
CHARLEY ELLIS: Well, I think
you should think about it.

00:53:42.221 --> 00:53:45.940
And this actually
gets to another thing

00:53:45.940 --> 00:53:47.990
that we do at
Wealthfront that I think

00:53:47.990 --> 00:53:56.070
is extremely valuable-- tactical
asset allocation, which is,

00:53:56.070 --> 00:53:59.460
gee, I don't like China now.

00:53:59.460 --> 00:54:02.140
I think I ought to be in Brazil.

00:54:02.140 --> 00:54:04.680
Or, I don't like
emerging markets.

00:54:04.680 --> 00:54:07.130
I think I ought to
be in the US market.

00:54:07.130 --> 00:54:08.540
I think that doesn't work.

00:54:08.540 --> 00:54:11.750
I've seen many
professionals try to do it.

00:54:11.750 --> 00:54:15.290
I think it simply
cannot be done.

00:54:15.290 --> 00:54:20.960
But what you can
do is rebalance.

00:54:20.960 --> 00:54:25.110
And what rebalancing
does is it simply says,

00:54:25.110 --> 00:54:27.640
let's say you thought
your portfolio ought

00:54:27.640 --> 00:54:36.740
to be, let's say 50% US,
25% developed foreign,

00:54:36.740 --> 00:54:38.210
25% emerging.

00:54:38.210 --> 00:54:40.470
I'm just making up the numbers.

00:54:40.470 --> 00:54:44.230
And then what you do is
at least once a year,

00:54:44.230 --> 00:54:46.350
you re-balance to that.

00:54:46.350 --> 00:54:49.450
And what that makes
you do is it makes

00:54:49.450 --> 00:54:53.270
you take some money off the
table on the market that

00:54:53.270 --> 00:54:57.270
did particularly well, and
makes you put the money back

00:54:57.270 --> 00:55:03.140
into the market that
did relatively poorly.

00:55:03.140 --> 00:55:06.510
If you want, it's the
opposite of what people do,

00:55:06.510 --> 00:55:08.830
because what people
actually do is

00:55:08.830 --> 00:55:11.880
they put more money into
the market that did well

00:55:11.880 --> 00:55:14.740
and take the money out of
the market that did poorly.

00:55:14.740 --> 00:55:21.060
And my own work suggests that
rebalancing over the last 15

00:55:21.060 --> 00:55:26.390
years-- and just once a year,
very simply-- added between one

00:55:26.390 --> 00:55:30.010
and two percentage
points to your return

00:55:30.010 --> 00:55:32.680
of a diversified portfolio.

00:55:32.680 --> 00:55:35.980
And that's one of the other
services of Wealthfront

00:55:35.980 --> 00:55:40.990
is that we do a
systematic rebalancing.

00:55:40.990 --> 00:55:44.080
I understand the argument
"couldn't we do it tactically?"

00:55:44.080 --> 00:55:46.600
And I just don't think
anybody knows how to do it.

00:55:46.600 --> 00:55:48.370
I don't know, Charley,
what your view is.

00:55:48.370 --> 00:55:50.870
CHARLEY ELLIS: Well, there are
people who know how to do it,

00:55:50.870 --> 00:55:51.850
but only briefly.

00:55:51.850 --> 00:55:53.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:53.220 --> 00:55:56.230
BURTON MALKIEL: Right,
not consistently.

00:55:56.230 --> 00:55:58.030
I mean, there will
always be people

00:55:58.030 --> 00:56:00.234
who get it right
once in a while.

00:56:00.234 --> 00:56:01.080
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:01.600
Thanks.

00:56:01.600 --> 00:56:03.019
ADAM NASH: Thank you.

00:56:03.019 --> 00:56:03.560
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:56:03.560 --> 00:56:04.270
My name is Tom.

00:56:04.270 --> 00:56:06.510
I was wondering, as more
and more people seem

00:56:06.510 --> 00:56:10.240
to take your advice and use
sort of a passive approach

00:56:10.240 --> 00:56:11.770
and stop picking
winners and losers,

00:56:11.770 --> 00:56:14.490
does there ever become a
tipping point in the future

00:56:14.490 --> 00:56:16.490
where it sort of
becomes the 1950s again,

00:56:16.490 --> 00:56:19.150
and since no one is
paying attention at all,

00:56:19.150 --> 00:56:22.337
it actually becomes possible
to pick winners and losers?

00:56:22.337 --> 00:56:23.170
CHARLEY ELLIS: Yeah.

00:56:23.170 --> 00:56:27.060
There is a point at which
it becomes, once again,

00:56:27.060 --> 00:56:28.850
a terrific opportunity.

00:56:28.850 --> 00:56:31.410
It's that time when
people say, I'm

00:56:31.410 --> 00:56:33.630
not going to be an
investment manager.

00:56:33.630 --> 00:56:35.150
There's no point in it.

00:56:35.150 --> 00:56:38.820
The pay have gone down so badly.

00:56:38.820 --> 00:56:42.180
You can get much better
jobs doing something else.

00:56:42.180 --> 00:56:45.840
It's going to come at a time
when the securities firms don't

00:56:45.840 --> 00:56:47.720
have analysts that
are pumping out

00:56:47.720 --> 00:56:50.394
a tremendous amount of
factual information,

00:56:50.394 --> 00:56:51.852
when Mike Bloomberg
says, you know,

00:56:51.852 --> 00:56:54.352
we're going to pull back all
those machines because nobody's

00:56:54.352 --> 00:56:55.360
subscribing anymore.

00:56:55.360 --> 00:56:57.340
We're going to junk them.

00:56:57.340 --> 00:56:58.850
There is a point.

00:56:58.850 --> 00:57:01.326
But walk through
the mathematics.

00:57:01.326 --> 00:57:06.660
A typical index fund will
have turnover of about 5%.

00:57:06.660 --> 00:57:09.680
The market as a whole has
turnover of about 100%,

00:57:09.680 --> 00:57:12.630
120%, somewhere in that range.

00:57:12.630 --> 00:57:17.910
So if you move 50% of
the assets into indexing,

00:57:17.910 --> 00:57:20.862
what fraction of the
market will that be?

00:57:20.862 --> 00:57:22.400
It's about 3%.

00:57:22.400 --> 00:57:28.040
If you move 80% into indexing,
a fraction of the total market

00:57:28.040 --> 00:57:30.160
activity, you're
starting to get close.

00:57:30.160 --> 00:57:34.320
When you get to 95% of
the money is now indexed,

00:57:34.320 --> 00:57:38.440
the amount of opportunity
off indexing would be high.

00:57:38.440 --> 00:57:40.360
But by then, all
those sad things

00:57:40.360 --> 00:57:42.660
I was talking about
earlier, people saying,

00:57:42.660 --> 00:57:45.210
this business is over,
I can't get a job.

00:57:45.210 --> 00:57:46.630
I can't get any equipment.

00:57:46.630 --> 00:57:48.620
I can't get any services.

00:57:48.620 --> 00:57:49.780
To hell with it.

00:57:49.780 --> 00:57:51.920
Then, we'll be back
with grass growing

00:57:51.920 --> 00:57:53.670
through the streets
of New York, and we'll

00:57:53.670 --> 00:57:55.590
have all kinds of
opportunities for people

00:57:55.590 --> 00:57:58.110
to get into active
investment management.

00:57:58.110 --> 00:58:00.800
But they'll be
alone, and they won't

00:58:00.800 --> 00:58:02.470
be able to get the
services and help,

00:58:02.470 --> 00:58:04.170
and so it won't work
for them anyway.

00:58:04.170 --> 00:58:07.810
I mean, this is one of those
marvelous mythical questions

00:58:07.810 --> 00:58:12.000
that I love your asking
it, because it's a setup.

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:14.000
In the reality,
the math, it just

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:16.040
doesn't work that
there will come

00:58:16.040 --> 00:58:18.350
a time there's so much
index that somebody ought

00:58:18.350 --> 00:58:22.552
to be really out there
doing active investing.

00:58:22.552 --> 00:58:24.010
BURTON MALKIEL:
Indexing has grown.

00:58:24.010 --> 00:58:31.460
I mean, it is getting close
to 25% of individual money,

00:58:31.460 --> 00:58:37.780
and probably close to a third of
institutional money is indexed.

00:58:37.780 --> 00:58:40.050
And when it gets to
be 95%, I'm going

00:58:40.050 --> 00:58:41.360
to worry about that question.

00:58:41.360 --> 00:58:44.480
But I'm with Charley.

00:58:44.480 --> 00:58:45.942
It's a good
theoretical question,

00:58:45.942 --> 00:58:47.775
but I don't think it's
ever going to happen.

00:58:47.775 --> 00:58:49.358
CHARLEY ELLIS: You
know that old poem?

00:58:49.358 --> 00:58:52.360
"Breathes there a man, with soul
so dead, who never to himself

00:58:52.360 --> 00:58:54.980
hath said, this is mine
own, my native land?"

00:58:54.980 --> 00:58:57.550
Well, it's the same thing
with active investing.

00:58:57.550 --> 00:59:00.230
We all believe we can do better.

00:59:00.230 --> 00:59:02.240
We all know from all
the other experiences

00:59:02.240 --> 00:59:05.550
that we have in our lives
that you can do better.

00:59:05.550 --> 00:59:07.980
It just happens in
this particular one,

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:10.400
if you're trying to
do better, you're

00:59:10.400 --> 00:59:13.030
up against an invisible
competition that

00:59:13.030 --> 00:59:16.970
is so damn good that it doesn't
make sense to be doing it.

00:59:16.970 --> 00:59:18.770
And I'm back to George
Plimpton going out

00:59:18.770 --> 00:59:20.770
and playing in the NFL.

00:59:20.770 --> 00:59:24.240
Nice guy, reasonably
strong, reasonably healthy,

00:59:24.240 --> 00:59:27.390
was six foot tall, but you
could get killed out there

00:59:27.390 --> 00:59:30.540
in the line playing against
a guy who weighs 300 pounds

00:59:30.540 --> 00:59:33.250
and does the 10-yard dash.

00:59:33.250 --> 00:59:34.220
Who wants to do that?

00:59:34.220 --> 00:59:35.427
Same problem.

00:59:35.427 --> 00:59:37.260
ADAM NASH: We have a
bunch of questions in--

00:59:37.260 --> 00:59:37.910
CHARLEY ELLIS:
Wonderful question.

00:59:37.910 --> 00:59:39.284
ADAM NASH: It's
a great question.

00:59:39.284 --> 00:59:41.650
We have a bunch of questions
in from remote viewers.

00:59:41.650 --> 00:59:43.550
So you can see them
ranked by popularity,

00:59:43.550 --> 00:59:46.080
so I'll just read
a couple of these.

00:59:46.080 --> 00:59:48.280
The first one is
actually a great one.

00:59:48.280 --> 00:59:50.700
It says, "Bonds are scary
because interest rates are

00:59:50.700 --> 00:59:53.340
low," and "Stocks are scary
because the economy has

00:59:53.340 --> 00:59:56.600
high unemployment and
profits are an all-time high

00:59:56.600 --> 00:59:59.240
due to a lot of cost cutting."

00:59:59.240 --> 01:00:02.864
Peter asks what should
he do with his cash.

01:00:02.864 --> 01:00:04.780
BURTON MALKIEL: Well, I
think bonds are scary,

01:00:04.780 --> 01:00:10.560
because I think when you look
at our dysfunctional government,

01:00:10.560 --> 01:00:17.810
and when you look at how hard it
is for us to rein in our budget

01:00:17.810 --> 01:00:22.450
deficit and do something about
our long-run budget deficit,

01:00:22.450 --> 01:00:30.860
you realize that we've got a
very high debt-to-GDP ratio,

01:00:30.860 --> 01:00:33.480
and the government's got
to do something about it.

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:36.960
Well, what the
government is doing

01:00:36.960 --> 01:00:41.550
is something that goes under
the name financial repression.

01:00:41.550 --> 01:00:45.280
We are keeping interest
rates very, very low.

01:00:45.280 --> 01:00:47.750
The last time the
10-year treasury

01:00:47.750 --> 01:00:52.640
yielded about 2 and 1/2%, which
it yields now-- it's actually

01:00:52.640 --> 01:00:57.190
up to 2.7% right now, but
it's somewhere around that--

01:00:57.190 --> 01:01:00.160
was in 1946.

01:01:00.160 --> 01:01:06.370
In 1946, we have a
debt-to-GDP ratio of 133%,

01:01:06.370 --> 01:01:08.670
much higher than it is now.

01:01:08.670 --> 01:01:11.370
And we were trying to
finance that deficit,

01:01:11.370 --> 01:01:17.450
and keeping interest
rates very, very low.

01:01:17.450 --> 01:01:22.030
Well, we actually had interest
rates pegged into the 1950s,

01:01:22.030 --> 01:01:27.500
and then we let them rise very,
very gradually until 1980.

01:01:27.500 --> 01:01:34.240
And what happened in 1980,
we had a moderate inflation.

01:01:34.240 --> 01:01:37.020
It was a little
bigger, and there

01:01:37.020 --> 01:01:40.110
was an oil and food
shock in the '70s.

01:01:40.110 --> 01:01:43.100
But in general, it was
a moderate inflation.

01:01:43.100 --> 01:01:48.790
And the debt-to-GDP ratio of the
United States in 1980 was 30%.

01:01:48.790 --> 01:01:52.750
So what this financial
repression does

01:01:52.750 --> 01:01:56.920
is it's a way of getting
rid of your debt,

01:01:56.920 --> 01:02:00.350
of letting inflation
inflate it away,

01:02:00.350 --> 01:02:03.470
and you do it on the
backs of the bondholders.

01:02:03.470 --> 01:02:06.910
And I am very
worried about that.

01:02:06.910 --> 01:02:12.900
And we at Wealthfront
have, I think,

01:02:12.900 --> 01:02:17.160
some very interesting strategies
in our asset allocation.

01:02:17.160 --> 01:02:22.640
For one thing, we use for part
of what might be the safer bond

01:02:22.640 --> 01:02:25.850
portfolio-- which is
still needed for people,

01:02:25.850 --> 01:02:30.400
particularly those who
worry about volatility--

01:02:30.400 --> 01:02:34.290
is we use an equity
substitution strategy.

01:02:34.290 --> 01:02:38.550
And by that, I mean we
try to use very safe,

01:02:38.550 --> 01:02:43.920
high-dividend growth stocks
to substitute for the bond

01:02:43.920 --> 01:02:44.630
portfolio.

01:02:44.630 --> 01:02:49.500
Just to give you an
example, AT&amp;T's stock

01:02:49.500 --> 01:02:52.840
yields something over 5%.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:56.320
And the dividend on AT&amp;T has
been growing at 5% a year.

01:02:56.320 --> 01:02:59.710
My guess is, it won't throw it
quite that rate in the future,

01:02:59.710 --> 01:03:01.570
but it's likely to grow.

01:03:01.570 --> 01:03:05.070
AT&amp;T 10-year bond's yield 4%.

01:03:05.070 --> 01:03:07.210
Now, I can't believe
that you won't

01:03:07.210 --> 01:03:12.750
be better off as an
investor with AT&amp;T stock.

01:03:12.750 --> 01:03:15.100
I think you'll get a
higher rate of return.

01:03:15.100 --> 01:03:19.250
And there was a time when
bond prices and yields were

01:03:19.250 --> 01:03:22.220
adjusting in the
1970s when bonds

01:03:22.220 --> 01:03:24.240
were more volatile than stocks.

01:03:24.240 --> 01:03:25.680
So that's some part of it.

01:03:25.680 --> 01:03:29.410
Another part of it is to look
at some foreign countries

01:03:29.410 --> 01:03:33.390
with budget deficits
under control,

01:03:33.390 --> 01:03:37.930
and with debt-to-GDP ratios
low, that have higher yields.

01:03:37.930 --> 01:03:42.970
So we're very conscious of that,
and have adjusted the asset

01:03:42.970 --> 01:03:48.050
allocation to take
advantage with of that.

01:03:48.050 --> 01:03:49.770
Stocks are scary.

01:03:49.770 --> 01:03:51.130
They're always scary.

01:03:51.130 --> 01:03:54.410
Profits are at an all-time high.

01:03:54.410 --> 01:04:00.550
On the other hand, because
we have high unemployment

01:04:00.550 --> 01:04:04.810
I don't think is a reason
to be negative on stocks.

01:04:04.810 --> 01:04:07.670
It means we've got a
lot of excess capacity,

01:04:07.670 --> 01:04:10.130
and we could in fact
grow as a nation

01:04:10.130 --> 01:04:11.970
at a much faster
rate in the future.

01:04:11.970 --> 01:04:14.380
In fact, my own
economic forecast

01:04:14.380 --> 01:04:16.680
is, we've been
growing at 2% a year.

01:04:16.680 --> 01:04:21.170
I think we're very likely to
see in 2014 a growth rate that's

01:04:21.170 --> 01:04:22.200
over 3%.

01:04:22.200 --> 01:04:26.060
So I think that's actually
an argument for stocks,

01:04:26.060 --> 01:04:32.160
because I think you're going to
see more growth in the future

01:04:32.160 --> 01:04:35.490
than you have in the past.

01:04:35.490 --> 01:04:41.210
And in general, our portfolio's
particularly for young people,

01:04:41.210 --> 01:04:46.100
are very much
equity-oriented, and we've

01:04:46.100 --> 01:04:49.870
been very careful about the
bonds with some of the ideas

01:04:49.870 --> 01:04:51.452
that I gave you earlier.

01:04:51.452 --> 01:04:52.910
CHARLEY ELLIS: Can
I add onto that?

01:04:52.910 --> 01:04:54.730
Because it's really
worth thinking about.

01:04:57.700 --> 01:05:00.780
Being young is the best
competitive advantage

01:05:00.780 --> 01:05:03.680
you could possibly
have as an investor,

01:05:03.680 --> 01:05:06.252
because you've got time.

01:05:06.252 --> 01:05:07.710
The big problem is
you haven't been

01:05:07.710 --> 01:05:09.126
around long enough
to realize what

01:05:09.126 --> 01:05:11.582
a terrific thing
it is to be young.

01:05:11.582 --> 01:05:13.290
BURTON MALKIEL: It's
wasted on the young?

01:05:13.290 --> 01:05:14.815
[LAUGHTER]

01:05:14.815 --> 01:05:16.440
CHARLEY ELLIS: You
can read Burt's book

01:05:16.440 --> 01:05:19.410
and that'll catch you up,
but that's a huge advantage

01:05:19.410 --> 01:05:21.940
to have time on your side.

01:05:21.940 --> 01:05:24.600
And most of the
people here are going

01:05:24.600 --> 01:05:28.400
to be investing, and buying
securities, and buying houses,

01:05:28.400 --> 01:05:31.590
and buying art, and
investing and accumulating

01:05:31.590 --> 01:05:35.200
for the next 30, 40 years.

01:05:35.200 --> 01:05:38.270
Most of you will work until 75.

01:05:38.270 --> 01:05:40.770
You'll enjoy the work so
much you won't want to stop.

01:05:40.770 --> 01:05:43.100
Then we'll move
retirement ages out.

01:05:43.100 --> 01:05:47.220
So 75 is a reasonable bet.

01:05:47.220 --> 01:05:51.930
Most of you are under 40,
so you've got a long shot.

01:05:51.930 --> 01:05:54.110
Even when you
retire, you're going

01:05:54.110 --> 01:05:57.650
to live for another 20
or 25 years after that.

01:05:57.650 --> 01:06:00.090
So your average length
of time between now

01:06:00.090 --> 01:06:03.030
and when you sell them to
pay for your way of living,

01:06:03.030 --> 01:06:04.310
it's not 35 years.

01:06:04.310 --> 01:06:07.870
It's 45 years.

01:06:07.870 --> 01:06:12.540
Nobody who's got 45 years would
say, ooh, let's buy bonds,

01:06:12.540 --> 01:06:15.940
unless they're anxious about
ups and downs in the market.

01:06:15.940 --> 01:06:18.450
If you just keep your
vision on the long distance

01:06:18.450 --> 01:06:21.150
and don't worry about the
ups and downs in the market,

01:06:21.150 --> 01:06:22.930
that's a calm under pressure.

01:06:22.930 --> 01:06:24.990
It's a tremendous advantage.

01:06:24.990 --> 01:06:28.140
Let me try one more
dimension of this.

01:06:28.140 --> 01:06:30.889
Everybody in this
room has got a job.

01:06:30.889 --> 01:06:32.930
Everybody in all the other
rooms that are tied in

01:06:32.930 --> 01:06:35.670
has got a job, with
a damn good company.

01:06:35.670 --> 01:06:39.800
Interesting place to work,
probably all are super smart,

01:06:39.800 --> 01:06:42.240
and know that they could
easily walk across the street

01:06:42.240 --> 01:06:44.440
and get a terrific job at
another really interesting

01:06:44.440 --> 01:06:46.150
company any time they wanted to.

01:06:46.150 --> 01:06:49.230
So security with
regard to earned income

01:06:49.230 --> 01:06:51.250
is very, very high.

01:06:51.250 --> 01:06:53.930
The only thing you don't
know is how rapidly you

01:06:53.930 --> 01:06:55.710
will rise in net earned income.

01:06:55.710 --> 01:06:57.400
You know in five
years from now, it's

01:06:57.400 --> 01:06:59.662
not going to be
less than it is now,

01:06:59.662 --> 01:07:01.370
unless you happen to
shoot the lights out

01:07:01.370 --> 01:07:04.460
with some spectacular bonus,
so once in a lifetime.

01:07:04.460 --> 01:07:05.560
Leave that aside.

01:07:05.560 --> 01:07:10.670
Salary, and regular bonuses,
whatever, compensation,

01:07:10.670 --> 01:07:13.660
is going to go clunkity
clunkity clunkity clunk.

01:07:13.660 --> 01:07:19.060
That's essentially an income
that is fixed-- on a slope,

01:07:19.060 --> 01:07:20.800
but it's fixed.

01:07:20.800 --> 01:07:24.180
Think of that as being
a bond equivalent.

01:07:24.180 --> 01:07:26.120
5%'s a reasonable interest rate.

01:07:26.120 --> 01:07:29.002
OK, multiply your salary by 20.

01:07:29.002 --> 01:07:31.210
That's how much you've got
in fixed income right now.

01:07:33.750 --> 01:07:37.170
That is such a big fraction
of your total wealth compared

01:07:37.170 --> 01:07:39.630
to what you've got in
securities investment.

01:07:39.630 --> 01:07:41.880
Look at the whole picture.

01:07:41.880 --> 01:07:46.240
I believe you will say, I want
to reconsider how much I have

01:07:46.240 --> 01:07:49.340
in stocks versus bonds,
because now that I realize

01:07:49.340 --> 01:07:54.290
I've got a fixed
income that is huge,

01:07:54.290 --> 01:07:57.280
I'm way behind on what I
ought to do in the stock area.

01:07:57.280 --> 01:08:01.280
I think most people who
are in their 30s and 40s

01:08:01.280 --> 01:08:04.740
should be thinking seriously
how much emotional stability

01:08:04.740 --> 01:08:07.960
they've got up to that level
that they can live with.

01:08:07.960 --> 01:08:09.790
They should be piling
everything they've

01:08:09.790 --> 01:08:13.910
got into equity type investing,
rather than into fixed income

01:08:13.910 --> 01:08:17.140
investing, because their
biggest thing they've got,

01:08:17.140 --> 01:08:20.380
their biggest value, is
their intellectual property,

01:08:20.380 --> 01:08:23.590
the ability come into an outfit
like Google and say, I'm here,

01:08:23.590 --> 01:08:25.170
and I'm willing
to work with you.

01:08:25.170 --> 01:08:28.550
What a fabulous sentence that
is to be able to say out loud.

01:08:31.430 --> 01:08:32.939
Recognize the reality.

01:08:32.939 --> 01:08:37.510
Your intellectual property
value is very large

01:08:37.510 --> 01:08:39.870
ADAM NASH: People in general
underestimate the value

01:08:39.870 --> 01:08:41.640
of that human capital asset.

01:08:41.640 --> 01:08:43.990
A lot of people in the
room, technology industry,

01:08:43.990 --> 01:08:46.870
we spend so much time keeping
our skills up to date.

01:08:46.870 --> 01:08:48.060
We learn the new languages.

01:08:48.060 --> 01:08:49.500
We learn the new platforms.

01:08:49.500 --> 01:08:52.740
We learn new solutions
to old problems.

01:08:52.740 --> 01:08:54.950
But that doesn't
always factor in to how

01:08:54.950 --> 01:08:56.259
people think about money.

01:08:56.259 --> 01:08:57.800
I want to be careful,
because we have

