We talked about this
briefly, but for folks

01:09:08.490 --> 01:09:10.740
in the audience who
may have a lump sum

01:09:10.740 --> 01:09:13.330
or have been out of the
market in some way, what

01:09:13.330 --> 01:09:16.010
are your opinions about lump
sum investing versus dollar cost

01:09:16.010 --> 01:09:16.510
averaging?

01:09:16.510 --> 01:09:18.176
CHARLEY ELLIS: I think
it's a great idea

01:09:18.176 --> 01:09:20.720
to put everything you've
got on the number that's

01:09:20.720 --> 01:09:23.390
going to work out
really, really well.

01:09:23.390 --> 01:09:26.470
When you're gambling, that's
exactly what you should do.

01:09:26.470 --> 01:09:29.020
And in investing, if you
just have the ability

01:09:29.020 --> 01:09:32.344
to time the market, you
should definitely do it.

01:09:32.344 --> 01:09:34.760
If, on the other hand, you're
like all those boring people

01:09:34.760 --> 01:09:38.910
that Burt and I know, real
human beings who could easily be

01:09:38.910 --> 01:09:44.060
misled and would rather
settle for normal,

01:09:44.060 --> 01:09:48.640
break it up into parts and
spread it out over some time.

01:09:48.640 --> 01:09:50.810
Don't try to be too
cute and clever.

01:09:50.810 --> 01:09:53.660
All you do is hurt yourself.

01:09:53.660 --> 01:09:56.890
If, for God's sake, you're
right, you'll then think,

01:09:56.890 --> 01:10:00.240
hey, you know, Burt,
I'm really good at this.

01:10:00.240 --> 01:10:01.420
I think I'll do it again.

01:10:01.420 --> 01:10:02.960
And you get at that time.

01:10:02.960 --> 01:10:05.492
Worse than that, you're
right the second time.

01:10:05.492 --> 01:10:07.950
Now, you're really in trouble,
because you'll honest-to-god

01:10:07.950 --> 01:10:10.030
believe you can do it.

01:10:10.030 --> 01:10:10.925
It will get you.

01:10:10.925 --> 01:10:12.430
ADAM NASH: You don't get
good at coin flipping?

01:10:12.430 --> 01:10:13.263
That doesn't happen?

01:10:13.263 --> 01:10:15.660
No?

01:10:15.660 --> 01:10:17.080
Burt, do you have
anything to add?

01:10:17.080 --> 01:10:17.871
BURTON MALKIEL: No.

01:10:17.871 --> 01:10:19.850
I think that says it very well.

01:10:19.850 --> 01:10:22.610
And as I suggested
to you, there's

01:10:22.610 --> 01:10:27.300
a little example that I
give of a market that's

01:10:27.300 --> 01:10:31.020
very volatile over five periods
and ends up exactly where

01:10:31.020 --> 01:10:34.230
it is, but goes down
first, and another market

01:10:34.230 --> 01:10:38.280
that goes up consistently.

01:10:38.280 --> 01:10:43.130
And you're actually
better off with the market

01:10:43.130 --> 01:10:48.640
that was very volatile, and
