01:10:48.640 --> 01:10:49.954
And it's much less risky.

01:10:49.954 --> 01:10:50.620
ADAM NASH: Yeah.

01:10:50.620 --> 01:10:52.411
The great thing about
dollar cost averaging

01:10:52.411 --> 01:10:55.889
is that you get in the
habit of putting money in,

01:10:55.889 --> 01:10:58.430
that first time that you realize
that the volatility actually

01:10:58.430 --> 01:11:02.180
works for you, that you ended
up putting in money last month

01:11:02.180 --> 01:11:05.265
and now the market-- you
realize it's actually

01:11:05.265 --> 01:11:06.470
a very boring process.

01:11:06.470 --> 01:11:09.050
You put in money continuously.

01:11:09.050 --> 01:11:11.150
Let the markets do their thing.

01:11:11.150 --> 01:11:13.720
I think there's one
more question here.

01:11:13.720 --> 01:11:17.050
AUDIENCE: I'd like to get
your thoughts on how indices

01:11:17.050 --> 01:11:20.710
are composed, whether or not
they be market cap based,

01:11:20.710 --> 01:11:24.540
fundamentally based, equal
weighting, anything like that.

01:11:24.540 --> 01:11:27.310
Just, what do you
think of those?

01:11:27.310 --> 01:11:30.310
BURTON MALKIEL: In
general, I believe

01:11:30.310 --> 01:11:35.332
in market capitalization
weighting.

01:11:35.332 --> 01:11:37.790
And this actually gets to one
of the other questions that's

01:11:37.790 --> 01:11:40.010
on the screen that
you didn't rated.

01:11:40.010 --> 01:11:43.610
When you think of it, let's
say you disagreed with me

01:11:43.610 --> 01:11:47.060
and you thought that markets
were really quite inefficient.

01:11:47.060 --> 01:11:51.150
You still ought to be an
indexer, because investing

01:11:51.150 --> 01:11:54.504
has got to be a zero sum game.

01:11:54.504 --> 01:11:56.670
CHARLEY ELLIS: Minus the
course of playing the game.

01:11:56.670 --> 01:11:59.290
BURTON MALKIEL: Well, yeah.

01:11:59.290 --> 01:12:01.234
If somebody has got
all the stocks that

01:12:01.234 --> 01:12:02.900
went up more than
average, somebody else

01:12:02.900 --> 01:12:04.890
has got to be holding
the ones that went down.

01:12:04.890 --> 01:12:07.360
But in fact, it's a
negative sum game,

01:12:07.360 --> 01:12:11.020
because of the costs involved.

01:12:11.020 --> 01:12:13.260
So the first thing
to remember is,

01:12:13.260 --> 01:12:17.560
once you stray from all the
stocks in the market which

01:12:17.560 --> 01:12:19.920
are weighted by their
market capitalization-- that

01:12:19.920 --> 01:12:24.290
is what the market is--
you are making a bet.

01:12:24.290 --> 01:12:27.330
And maybe would
be right, but then

01:12:27.330 --> 01:12:30.240
somebody else has
got to be wrong.

01:12:30.240 --> 01:12:33.150
Now, what all of
the other things

01:12:33.150 --> 01:12:36.450
do-- whether it's equal
weighting, whether it's

01:12:36.450 --> 01:12:44.050
fundamental indexing, whether
it's value investing-- is

01:12:44.050 --> 01:12:49.400
you put certain tilts
into your portfolio.

01:12:49.400 --> 01:12:52.280
Fundamental indexing
has been very popular.

01:12:52.280 --> 01:12:55.580
There, you weight by
the company's earnings,

01:12:55.580 --> 01:12:58.340
or its sales, or its book value.

01:12:58.340 --> 01:13:02.230
And what that does is it puts
two tilts into your portfolio,

01:13:02.230 --> 01:13:07.100
it makes your portfolio slightly
more small cap than large cap,

01:13:07.100 --> 01:13:09.820
and it makes your
portfolio slightly more

01:13:09.820 --> 01:13:16.500
quote "value," if we define
value as having lower price

01:13:16.500 --> 01:13:19.470
earnings and lower
price-to-book value.

01:13:19.470 --> 01:13:25.230
There have been lots of periods
where those tilts have worked.

01:13:25.230 --> 01:13:29.950
And there's a big
dispute in the academy.

01:13:29.950 --> 01:13:32.660
Is it because markets
are inefficient,

01:13:32.660 --> 01:13:36.160
or is it because of risk?

01:13:36.160 --> 01:13:39.370
I think the people who
favor these sorts of things

01:13:39.370 --> 01:13:42.730
better think it's risk, because
if it's in an efficiency,

01:13:42.730 --> 01:13:45.920
somebody's going to arbitrage
it away in the future.

01:13:45.920 --> 01:13:48.110
But let's say you
believe in that

01:13:48.110 --> 01:13:50.770
and that that's what you want.

01:13:50.770 --> 01:13:51.630
I don't.

01:13:51.630 --> 01:13:56.870
I want to be a capital market
capitalization indexer.

01:13:56.870 --> 01:14:00.050
But let's say you think
that-- this is something

01:14:00.050 --> 01:14:02.050
that has worked in
certain past periods.

01:14:02.050 --> 01:14:03.490
There's no question about it.

01:14:03.490 --> 01:14:06.200
And you think it's going
to work in the future.

01:14:06.200 --> 01:14:11.780
If you want that, don't
buy the fundamental index.

01:14:11.780 --> 01:14:18.230
Buy a Vanguard value index
at a very, very low fee.

01:14:18.230 --> 01:14:22.170
Realize what tilts are in
those kinds of portfolios.

01:14:22.170 --> 01:14:25.100
Or buy small cap,
which is-- in fact,

01:14:25.100 --> 01:14:28.952
we've got some
weighting of small cap

01:14:28.952 --> 01:14:31.390
in our overall portfolios.

01:14:31.390 --> 01:14:33.580
And by it at a low fee.

01:14:33.580 --> 01:14:37.870
Don't buy these things that are
advertised, like fundamentally

01:14:37.870 --> 01:14:40.440
index-weighted portfolios,
because they've

01:14:40.440 --> 01:14:42.130
got a much higher fee.

01:14:42.130 --> 01:14:45.270
And it's a great for the
purveyor of the investment

01:14:45.270 --> 01:14:47.930
product, and not
so good for you.

01:14:47.930 --> 01:14:51.830
And look, I think all of us
who talk about the stock market

01:14:51.830 --> 01:14:55.850
need to be very modest
about what we know and don't

01:14:55.850 --> 01:14:58.130
know about the stock market.

01:14:58.130 --> 01:15:01.950
But the only thing I'll tell
you that I am 100% sure of,

01:15:01.950 --> 01:15:04.440
and that is at the
lower the fee I pay

01:15:04.440 --> 01:15:06.710
to the purveyor of the
investment product,

01:15:06.710 --> 01:15:10.110
the more there's
going to be for me.

